In case you're running out of A.E. Housman to quote in the Olympia
Times, I would suggest Edna St. Vincent Millay.  It's much of the same
subject matter (death, pathos, etc.), but from a woman's point of
view.  Here's one of her lighter verses that I like to quote:


		    Midnight Oil

	Cut if you will, with Sleep's dull knife,
	    Each day to half its length, my friend --
	The years that Time takes off *my* life,
	    He'll take from off the other end!

		        -- Edna St. Vincent Millay


And, as put more succinctly:

         I'll sleep when I'm dead.

		        -- Warren Zevon

